			<h3 ><a href="#p1693571">Re: Bidding on Ebay; Ignorance on best Bidding strategy</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=1693571&amp;sid=32f634186e869c535397d6396fbe3059#p1693571"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=17168&amp;sid=32f634186e869c535397d6396fbe3059">daytona084</a></strong> &raquo; Sun May 12, 2013 3:02 pm </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>nisiprius wrote:</cite><br /><span style="font-weight: bold">Please answer the question directly.</span> I place a bid early on with a $29 maximum. How do you manage to get that item for less than $29 by &quot;waiting until the last few seconds?&quot; </div></blockquote><br /><br />nisi:<br /><br />You seem to have a blind spot here. Are you aware that on eBay, if you bid $29 (using your example) and you are the high bidder, you do not necessarily pay $29? The purchase price is the second-highest bid plus the &quot;increment&quot;. For example, if you bid $29 and the second highest bid was $10, you would win the item for $10.50 ($0.50 is the increment at that level).</div>

			

		</div>

		
