			<h3 ><a href="#p1695117">Re: Bidding on Ebay; Ignorance on best Bidding strategy</a></h3>
			<p class="author"><a href="./viewtopic.php?p=1695117&amp;sid=32f634186e869c535397d6396fbe3059#p1695117"><img src="./styles/prosilver/imageset/icon_post_target.gif" width="11" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" /></a>by <strong><a href="./memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=28806&amp;sid=32f634186e869c535397d6396fbe3059">bertilak</a></strong> &raquo; Tue May 14, 2013 10:56 am </p>

			

			<div class="content"><blockquote><div><cite>deanbrew wrote:</cite>I'm not sure how else I can explain it, but I've used sniping for many years, and it works when there are few bidders and doesn't when there are more than a couple of bidders.</div></blockquote><br />Overall an excellent description and it covers an aspect not mentioned before, that is, the situations where it is most and least favorable. (This is from the buyers' perspective.)<br /><br />Two additional points, or expansions on the points you already made...<br /><br /><ul><li>It does not contribute to the unfavorable condition (multiple active bidders), marginally reducing the chances of that happening.</li><li>Even when it doesn't help, it doesn't hurt, either. There is an up-side but no down-side.</li></ul></div>

			<div id="sig1695117" class="signature">No-one really listens to anyone else, and if you try it sometime you will see why. | -- Mignon McLaughlin</div>

